==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Bight
<hw>Bight</hw> <pr>(b⟦imac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>bi⟦yogh⟧t</ets> a bending; cf. Sw. & Dan. <ets>bugt</ets> bend,
bay; fr. AS. <ets>byht</ets>, fr. <ets>b⟦umac⟧gan</ets>. ⟦root⟧88. Cf.
<er>Bout</er>, <er>Bought</er> a bend, and see <er>Bow</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A corner, bend, or angle; a
hollow; <as>as, the <ex>bight</ex> of a horse's knee; the <ex>bight</ex>
of an elbow</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A bend in a coast forming an open
bay; <as>as, the <ex>Bight</ex> of Benin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The double part of a rope when
folded, in distinction from the ends; that is, a round, bend, or coil
not including the ends; a loop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Biglandular</ent>⟦br⟧
